After removing bad performers, we can aggregate by congruity and scene type to look at performance. We will first code the scene type in two “sparse vs cluttered”

# Aggregate
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change") %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity) %>% 
  summarise(mean_acc = mean(cd_acc),
            sd_acc = sd(cd_acc))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Plot
make_plot(agg_data, agg_data$mean_acc, "Mean acc by congruity")

Compute performance at encoding

And now look at performance as RTs

# Aggregate
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change", cd_acc == 1) %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity) %>% 
  summarise(mean_rt = mean(cd_rt, na.rm = T),

Detection efficiency

Let’s compute the detection efficiency index

# Compute as acc/RT
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change") %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity) %>% 
  summarise(mean_acc = mean(cd_acc), sd_acc = sd(cd_acc),
            mean_rt = mean(cd_rt, na.rm = T), sd_rt = sd(cd_rt, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  mutate(eff_ind = mean_acc/mean_rt) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Plot
make_plot(agg_data, agg_data$eff_ind, "Mean efficiency by congruity")
## Warning: Removed 10 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).
## Warning: Removed 10 rows containing non-finite values (stat_summary).
## Warning: Removed 10 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 10 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

Compute rANOVA

I will compute a 2 repeated measures ANOVA with scene-object congruity (congruent vs. incongruent) as within-subjects factor.

# Need to select only the to-be-used columns
data_to_stat <-  subset(x = agg_data, select = c(participant, congruity, eff_ind))

# Run ANOVA
res.aov <- anova_test(data = data_to_stat, dv = eff_ind, wid = participant, within = congruity)
## Warning: NA detected in rows: 11,12,15,16,23,24,25,26,27,28.
## Removing this rows before the analysis.
get_anova_table(res.aov)
## ANOVA Table (type III tests)
## 
##      Effect DFn DFd     F     p p<.05   ges
## 1 congruity   1  13 0.823 0.381       0.004
# Pair-wise comparisons
pwc <- data_to_stat %>%
  pairwise_t_test(
    eff_ind ~ congruity, paired = TRUE,
    p.adjust.method = "bonferroni"
  )
pwc
## # A tibble: 1 × 10
##   .y.     group1 group2    n1    n2 statistic    df     p p.adj p.adj.signif
## * <chr>   <chr>  <chr>  <int> <int>     <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <chr>       
## 1 eff_ind 1      2         19    19    -0.907    13 0.381 0.381 ns

Identification

# Aggregate
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change") %>% 
  filter(cd_acc == 1) %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity) %>% 
  summarise(mean_id = mean(id_acc, na.rm = T),
            sd_id = sd(id_acc, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
